{{No references|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox book | name = National Lampoon 1964 High School Yearbook Parody | title_orig = | image = | author = [[P. J. O'Rourke]] (editor) and [[Douglas Kenney|Doug Kenney]] (Editor) | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | genre = [[Parody]] | publisher = | release_date = | media_type = Print ([[hardback]]) | pages = 176 pp | isbn = | oclc = }}
'''''National Lampoon 1964 High School Yearbook Parody''''' is an American humor book that was first published in 1973. It was a spin-off from ''[[National Lampoon (magazine)|National Lampoon]]'' magazine. The book was a parody of a high school yearbook from the early 1960s. It was edited by [[P. J. O'Rourke]] and [[Douglas Kenney|Doug Kenney]] and art-directed by [[David Kaestle]]. Much of the writing was by [[P. J. O'Rourke]] and [[Douglas Kenney|Doug Kenney]]. The "literary magazine" was written by [[Sean Kelly (writer)|Sean Kelly]]; the sports page was by [[Christopher Cerf (musician and television producer)|Christopher Cerf]]; and the Principal's Letter and the "In Memorium" piece were both by [[Ed Subitzky]].
The book, as it was originally published, appeared to be a genuine 1964 yearbook from '''"[[Estes Kefauver|C. Estes Kefauver]] High School"''': the ''Kefauver Kaleidoscope''. Senator Kefauver himself had only died the year before, in 1963. The school is located in "Dacron, Ohio" (a reference to the city [[Akron, Ohio]],<ref>Akron is the metropolitan area nearest Sandusky, Ohio--setting of ''The King of Sandusky'', a fictionalised account of O'Rourke's childhood</ref> and to inexpensive synthetic fabric [[Dacron]].)
The parody is closely based on the Toledo, Ohio's [[DeVilbiss High School (Toledo, Ohio)|DeVilbiss High School]] yearbook, called the ''Pot 'o Gold''. O'Rourke attended DHS for a couple of years in the early 1960s. The swim team photo caption contains the names of a number of O'Rourke's friends from Devilbiss. Like many great parodies, the Lampoon yearbook is only a degree or two from the original.
The publication also included a copy of the school newspaper, a [[basketball]] program, a [[report card]], a [[diploma]], [[School detention|detention]] slips and a fake [[Identity document|ID]]. According to apparent inscriptions, the book belonged to "Larry Kroger", class of '64. The character Larry Kroger went on to become the college freshman [[protagonist]] (played by [[Tom Hulce]]) of the comedy movie ''[[National Lampoon's Animal House]]'', released in 1978. The character "Mandy Pepperidge" also makes her first appearance in the Yearbook and reappears in the film (played by [[Mary Louise Weller]]).
Five years after the Yearbook parody, in 1978, the National Lampoon published the ''[[National Lampoon Sunday Newspaper Parody]]'', a fake Sunday newspaper which also claimed to originate in "Dacron, Ohio" but was contemporary, being dated Sunday February 12, 1978.
