[[File:Teotig 1905.jpg|thumb|Teotig in 1905]]
'''Teotoros "Teotig" Lapçinciyan''' ({{lang-hy|Թեոդորոս "Թեոդիկ" Լափչինճյան}}, 1873; [[Üsküdar]], [[Constantinople]] ([[Istanbul]]), [[Ottoman Empire]] – 1928; [[Paris]], [[France]])<ref name="Soulahian-Kuyumjian 252">{{cite book|last=Soulahian-Kuyumjian|first=Rita|title=Teotig: Biography|publisher=[[Gomidas Institute]]|location=London, England|isbn=1-903656-93-1|pages=252|type=paperback|date=April 6, 2010}}</ref> was an [[Armenian people|Armenian]] writer and publisher best known for his [[Armenian language]] [[almanac]], ''[[Amenun Daretsuytsi]]'' (in [[Armenian language|Armenian]] Ամէնուն Տարեցոյցը meaning "Everyone’s Almanac").<ref name="Kuyumjian Trilogy of Teotig">{{cite web|title=Kuyumjian Trilogy Presentation in New Jersey on Andonian and Teotig|url=http://www.mirrorspectator.com/2011/04/29/kuyumjian-trilogy-presentation-in-new-jersey-on-andonian-and-teotig/|work=Armenians News Source|publisher=Armenian Mirror Spector|accessdate=8 October 2011}}</ref> It was published annually, mostly in [[Constantinople]], between 1907 and 1929.<ref name="Soulahian-Kuyumjian 252"/><ref name="Kuyumjian Trilogy of Teotig"/>
Teotig was born in 1873 to [[Armenian people|Armenian]] parents in [[Üsküdar]], a district of Constantinople situated on the Asiatic side of the Bosphorus.<ref name="Kuyumjian Trilogy of Teotig"/> He married writer [[Arshaguhi Teotig|Arşaguhi Cezveciyan]] in 1902.<ref>{{cite web|title=Remembering Teotig|url=http://hayatoldugugibi.blogspot.com/2006/09/teotigi-anmsarken.html|accessdate=8 October 2011|language=Turkish}}</ref> Aside from his yearly [[Almanac]] production, Teotig was also known for his "Golgotha of the Armenian Clergy",<ref name="Soulahian-Kuyumjian 252"/><ref name="Movsesian">{{cite web|last=Movsesian|first=Father Vazken|title=Teotig: The Golgotha of the Armenian Clergy|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:lPUlocStgpIJ:www.armenews.com/IMG/Teotig_Data_Base-Intro.doc+teotig+golgotha&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEEShaFA3DXMeF_wtFRpd10BDAgkqfqsXk0UnmCq1YGdwm-lmOQ_d0MQ06W5jCmAzSA2SFiYNW0OWpWg2HCQ9pg4G61ejGu5f87yScbHtW89wywcgSCwjAfypSHyVs27l8W91qlfxv&sig=AHIEtbTBw8JZSfxJeQ6tit2qCtqYtfjiQA|accessdate=8 October 2011|date=June 30, 2006}}</ref> a compilation of sources analyzing the priests, clergymen, and monks who were massacred during the [[Armenian genocide]]. He ended up compiling and documenting 1252 witnesses to the massacres of the clergy.<ref name="Movsesian"/> Teotig was assisted in his enterprise by his British-educated wife, Arshaguhi Teotig (1875-1921)—herself a writer and educator—until her untimely death.
Teotig himself was deported during the [[Armenian Genocide]] and managed to survive.<ref name="Soulahian-Kuyumjian 252"/> After returning to Constantinople in 1922, he fled to Europe on the eve of its occupation by the army of Mustafa Kemal. He then lived a wandering life for the next six years, living in Corfu, Nicosia, and Paris, with the last of his yearbooks being printed in Venice, Vienna, and Paris. He died in May 1928 in Paris, when the 18th volume of his yearbooks (his "paper children", as he called them) was in press. His son Vahakn Teotig died in the United States sometime in the 1960s.<ref name="Soulahian-Kuyumjian 252"/>
