{{more footnotes|date=September 2012}}
{{Infobox book |name=Terror Television American Series 1970-1999 |author=[[John Kenneth Muir]] |genre= |country=United States |language=English |publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]] |pages=685}} '''''Terror Television American Series 1970–1999''''' is an American [[Reference work|reference]] book by [[John Kenneth Muir]] that documents television [[Horror film|horror]] shows from 1970 to 1999.<ref>{{cite book|title=Chiller Theater Magazine|year=2002|page=57}}</ref><ref>Adam, Anthony J. "Terror Television: American Series, 1970-1999. (Reference Books)." ''Reference & User Services Quarterly'' Winter 2001: 196+. ''Academic OneFile''. Web. 3 Oct. 2012. Gale Document Number: GALE|A83034412</ref>
==Format== The book is categorized into three parts. Part 1, "The Horror Series", chronicles three types of programs. First the anthology series features shows including ''[[Night Gallery]]'', ''[[Tales from the Darkside]]'', ''[[Tales from the Crypt (TV series)|Tales from the Crypt]]'', Second the adventure format includes shows like ''[[The X-Files]]'', ''[[Kolchak: the Night Stalker]]'' and ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (TV series)|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]''. Third the soap opera format including ''[[Twin Peaks]]'', ''[[Kindred: the Embraced]]'' and ''[[American Gothic (1995 TV series)|American Gothic]]''. Part 2, "If It Sounds Like Horror..." features series including ''[[Amazing Stories]]'', ''[[The Munsters Today]]'', ''[[Nowhere Man (TV series)|Nowhere Man]]'' and ''[[Sabrina, the Teenage Witch (1996 TV series)|Sabrina, the Teenage Witch]]''. Part 3, "Further Thoughts" compiles lists including the 10 Best and 10 worst terror television shows.
==Reception== ''[[Booklist]]'' gave a positive review citing it as "useful" and praising the author's dedication.<ref>{{cite web |title=Booklist Review: 1 Sept. 2001 |url=http://www.booklistonline.com/Terror-Television-American-Series-1970-1999-John-Kenneth-Muir/pid=189469 |work=[[Booklist]] |accessdate=4 October 2012}}</ref>
